<subSubSection id="C3261DE06662FFFB1984F940FD69EB16" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B834E6B6662FFFB1984F940FD69EB16" blockId="6.[192,1440,1651,1899]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis id="B94892796662FFFB1984F940FE87EB76" box="[240,350,1779,1803]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Remarks</emphasis>
. The common, introduced, Asian paradoxosomatid is ubiquitous in southern 
<collectingCountry id="F32B0EFB6662FFFB1C7FF940FAB2EB76" box="[1291,1387,1779,1803]" name="Canada" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Canada</collectingCountry>
and the lower 48 states. It should be expected in municipalities and urban environments throughout both Dakotas and Minnesota. Gonopodal and somatic illustrations are available in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD339A6662FFFB1DFDF880FAE4EB36" author="Shelley, R. M." box="[1161,1341,1843,1867]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" pagination="37 - 79" refId="ref15492" refString="Shelley, R. M. 1978. Millipeds of the eastern Piedmont region of North Carolina, U. S. A. (Diplopoda). Journal of Natural History 12: 37 - 79." type="journal article" year="1978">Shelley (1978)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD339A6662FFFB1C3CF880FEC9EB16" author="Blower, J. G." pageId="6" pageNumber="5" pagination="1 - 242" refId="ref13294" refString="Blower, J. G. 1985. Millipedes. Synopses of the British Fauna (New Series) 35: 1 - 242 + i-vii." type="journal article" year="1985">Blower (1985)</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD339A6662FFFB183BF8E0FD75EB16" author="Shelley, R. M. &amp; P. T. Lehtinen" box="[335,684,1875,1899]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" pagination="81 - 94" refId="ref16065" refString="Shelley, R. M., and P. T. Lehtinen. 1998. Introduced millipeds of the family Paradoxosomatidae on Pacific Islands (Diplopoda: Polydesmida). Arthropoda Selecta 7 (2): 81 - 94." type="journal article" year="1998">Shelley and Lehtinen (1998)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
